Observation Details: Photo:

Having observed four fledglings, in a grassy area next to the parking lot, just the previous day, I was saddened to see that one was missing this morning and that the family had moved from the grass to the parking lot. I stayed in my car, a good distance away and knew they were comfortable in my being there because they actually moved in closer to the car after I sat there for a while.  Later and much to my astonishment the three fledglings, encouraged by the mother, attempted to cross the four sets of train tracks (and three hot rails) in an effort to get to the Hudson river.   The Sunday  morning train schedule allowed for fewer trains passing through but it was still hard to watch. After moving to a new location, I lost sight of two of the fledglings and feared the worst when the mother stopped vocalizing.  But following up exactly one week later, I was so very happy to observe the entire family of five at the Landing "beach" on the Hudson river. The three fledglings all looked exactly one week older. I guess the mother knew what she was doing after all!

There was another pair who successfully distracted me with broken wing displays so I'm unsure of where theirs was, or if they already hatched young somewhere, but I was nervously staring at the ground with every step because of how boisterous their displays were. They were quite far off with the displays, too. All photos were taken at full zoom.

Observation Details: 2 adultos, macho y hembra, 4 pichones y 1 huevo aún sin eclosionar. Interesante la época, finales de setiembre, cuando se supone que los pichones nacen entre mayo y julio. En algunos lugares como Puerto Rico, según leo, se reproducen todo el año, supongo que en Costa Rica entonces también. El nido está sobre un lote baldío que está siendo trabajado con movimiento de tierra para urbanizar. Los tractores pasan cerca pero no se han acercado a más de unos 30 metros del nido, por dicha. Una tarde vi un coyote merodeando en la tarde, cerca del nido, me llamó la atención que los adultos estaban relativamente cerca del coyote, supongo que distrayéndolo y alejándolo del nido. Los coyotes son comunes ahí, suenen casi todas las noches, pero esa tarde lo vi a luz de día.

Observation Details: Having observed four fledglings, in a grassy area next to the parking lot, just the previous day, I was saddened to see that one was missing this morning and that the family had moved from the grass to the parking lot. I stayed in my car, a good distance away and knew they were comfortable in my being there because they actually moved in closer to the car after I sat there for a while.  Later and much to my astonishment the three fledglings, encouraged by the mother, attempted to cross the four sets of train tracks (and three hot rails) in an effort to get to the Hudson river.   The Sunday  morning train schedule allowed for fewer trains passing through but it was still hard to watch. After moving to a new location, I lost sight of two of the fledglings and feared the worst when the mother stopped vocalizing.  But following up exactly one week later, I was so very happy to observe the entire family of five at the Landing "beach" on the Hudson river. The three fledglings all looked exactly one week older. I guess the mother knew what she was doing after all!

Observation Details: About 5 juveniles with parents trying to keep them together in the middle of the field.  I first noticed them when I saw a much larger than normal Killdeer - the binocular view showed the parent was simply keeping some chicks warm and dry on this cold and rainy day.  Suddenly another chick appeared and this caused the group to break-up, with the chicks going into two groups of two and the parent in a different direction.  There were dogs running around further down the field, but that didn't seem to bother them much.  There was a lot of Killdeer calling and chirps from the group as they tried to stay close together.

A Killdeer nests on the stones above the wall around the club pool deck almost every summer. I saw the mother there a few weeks ago and the fledglings Saturday and came back as a guest of a shareholder to photograph them today. I used a zoom lens and cropped heavily, staying back to prevent mama from worrying. My first look at fledgling Killdeer.

Media notes: They only called an alarm when the Sharpie circled near the freeway.
Observation Details: (more than 27) 26 on the parking lot sunning and 1 heard on the dirt lot. Four minutes into photographing them on the parking lot, there were alarm calls.  One bird flew back to the dirt lot and called an alarm, the rest on the asphalt scattered on the parking lot.  A few seconds later, more alarm calls and flock flew in a frenzy into the dirt lot, with a small flock of about 12 taking off again and flying together toward 166th and circling around, away from the rest of the flock.  The hawk didn't even bother to circle close to the flock; it stayed by the freeway and hunted south.
